# rwsdk Router API: Non-Rendering HTTP Endpoints

## 1. Imports from `"rwsdk/router"`

The package.json export map confirms:

```json
"./router": {
  "types": "./dist/runtime/entries/router.d.ts",
  "workerd": "./dist/runtime/entries/router.js",
  "default": "./dist/runtime/entries/routerClient.js"
}
```

The entry point (`dist/runtime/entries/router.d.ts`) re-exports everything from `../lib/router` and `../lib/links`. So from `"rwsdk/router"` you can import:

```ts
import {
  // Route definition functions
  route,       // define a route with a path pattern
  index,       // define the root "/" route
  prefix,      // prefix a group of routes under a path
  layout,      // wrap routes with a layout component
  render,      // wrap routes with a Document component + rendering options
  except,      // define an error handler

  // App definition
  defineRoutes,  // create a router from route definitions

  // Utility
  matchPath,     // test if a path matches a route pattern
  wrapHandlerToThrowResponses,
  isClientReference,

  // Links (from ../lib/links)
  defineLinks,
  createLinks,
  linkFor,

  // Types (from ../lib/types)
  DocumentProps,
  LayoutProps,
} from "rwsdk/router";
```

## 2. How to Define a Route That Returns JSON (Not HTML)

There are **two approaches**, both using the `route()` function:

### Approach A: Return a `Response` directly from the handler

The handler function receives a `RequestInfo` object and can return a `Response`. The router detects `Response` objects and sends them directly — no React rendering occurs:

```ts
import { route } from "rwsdk/router";

route("/api/search", function handler({ request }) {
  const url = new URL(request.url);
  const query = url.searchParams.get("q") || "";

  return Response.json({
    query,
    results: [],
  });
});
```

This works because the handler's return type is `MaybePromise<Response>` (see `RouteFunction<T>` in the types below). When the router sees a `Response`, it short-circuits and returns it immediately.

### Approach B: Method-based routing (per-HTTP-method handlers)

Use an object with HTTP method keys instead of a single handler function. Each method handler can return a `Response`:

```ts
import { route } from "rwsdk/router";

route("/api/users", {
  get: () => Response.json(users),
  post: async ({ request }) => {
    const body = await request.json();
    return Response.json({ status: "created" }, { status: 201 });
  },
  delete: () => new Response(null, { status: 204 }),
});
```

Supported method verbs: `"delete" | "get" | "head" | "patch" | "post" | "put"`. You can also define custom HTTP methods via the `custom` property:

```ts
route("/api/data", {
  custom: {
    purge: () => new Response(null, { status: 204 }),
  },
});
```

The router automatically handles `OPTIONS` requests (returns `Allow` header) and returns `405 Method Not Allowed` for unsupported methods (both can be disabled via `config: { disableOptions: true, disable405: true }`).

## 3. Accessing the Raw `Request` Object

The handler function receives a `RequestInfo` object (not the raw `Request` directly). The `RequestInfo` type is:

```ts
// dist/runtime/requestInfo/types.d.ts
interface RequestInfo<Params = any, AppContext = DefaultAppContext> {
  request: Request;           // ← THE RAW REQUEST OBJECT
  path: string;               // the matched URL pathname
  params: Params;             // route parameters (:id, etc.)
  ctx: AppContext;            // application context (e.g., user session)
  rw: RwContext;              // internal SDK context
  cf: ExecutionContext;       // Cloudflare Workers execution context
  response: ResponseInit & {
    headers: Headers;
  };
  isAction: boolean;
}
```

